******
[1] Brazil (Tocantins)
Date: Mon 7 Nov 2022
Source: globo.com [in Portuguese, machine trans., edited]
https://g1.globo.com/to/tocantins/noticia/2022/11/07/estado-registra-74-casos-de-leishmaniose-visceral-e-tres-mortes-pela-doenca.ghtml


Tocantins recorded 74 cases of visceral leishmaniasis and 3 deaths from the disease between January and October this year [2022]. The data were released this Monday [7 Nov 2022] by the State Department of Health (SES-TO).

Visceral leishmaniasis is a serious vector-borne disease that, if left untreated, can lead to death in more than 90% of cases. One of the deaths took place in Paraíso do Tocantins and another 2 in Porto Nacional.

Another form of the disease is cutaneous leishmaniasis, which had 250 confirmed cases in Tocantins this year [2022]. No deaths were recorded.

The disease cycle involves dogs as hosts and the "straw mosquito" ["mosquito palhas," but presumably meaning _Lutzomyia_ sandflies - Ed.], which is the vector responsible for the transmission of the disease. The disease control plan is made by calculating the risk in each municipality, drawing up action plans with strategies to be implemented throughout the year.

"Basically, the focus is diagnosis, and treating all possible human cases. In due course, carry out educational and social mobilization activities, in addition to actions aimed at controlling reservoirs/hosts [dogs] and vectors", explained Júlio Bigel, technical advisor at SES.

According to SES, the state started the control program with the collaring of dogs in municipalities with the highest risk of contamination. The action is done with collars impregnated with insecticide to try to control the disease.

For early diagnosis, people should be aware of the clinical manifestations of the disease, both in children and adults. Symptoms include an enlarged abdomen and long-lasting fevers.

The diagnosis can be made by means of rapid and laboratory tests, which are performed at the Central Public Health Laboratory of Tocantins (Lacen). The test is also made available in the municipalities by municipal laboratories and health units.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED Rapporteur Mahmoud Orabi

[According to WHO figures, Brazil accounts for 96% of all cases of human visceral leishmaniasis (HVL) in the Americas. Canine VL is also widespread, with up to 20% of dogs infected in the highly endemic localities. The fatality rate related to HVL and cases of HVL-HIV coinfection have increased over the years (https://leishinfowho-cc55.es/country-profiles/b/).

Tocantins is a state in central Brazil. According to an area risk classification of HVL in Brazil, certain municipalities in the central and northern portions of Tocantins have intense transmission and high average case counts of HVL (see Figures 1 and 4 in Ref. 1). The OneHealth approach taken by the Tocantins public health authorities, which includes measures to prevent and control the infection is dogs, is commendable. Unfortunately, nationwide interventions implemented under the Brazilian Visceral Leishmaniasis Surveillance and Control Programme have not been successful in reducing transmission and human cases, especially in urban areas (Refs. 2,3).

References:
1. Machado, G., Alvarez, J., Bakka, H.C. et al. Revisiting area risk classification of visceral leishmaniasis in Brazil. BMC Infect Dis 19, 2 (2019). https://doi.org/10.1186/s12879-018-3564-0
2. da Rocha, I.C.M., dos Santos, L.H.M., Coura-Vital, W. et al. Effectiveness of the Brazilian Visceral Leishmaniasis Surveillance and Control Programme in reducing the prevalence and incidence of Leishmania infantum infection. Parasites Vectors 11, 586 (2018). https://doi.org/10.1186/s13071-018-3166-0
3. Leishmaniasis. Epidemiological Report of the Americas. December 2019 https://iris.paho.org/bitstream/handle/10665.2/50505/Leishreport2019_eng.pdf - Mod.LXL]

