[2] Argentina (Misiones)
[A]
Date: Mon 7 Nov 2022
Source: Primera Edicion [in Spanish, machine trans., abridged, edited]
https://www.primeraedicion.com.ar/nota/100649756/un-hombre-de-eldorado-se-encuentra-internado-por-leishmaniasis-visceral/


Misiones Public Health issued an alert for a suspected case of visceral Leishmaniasis. According to the official report, the case is a 34-year-old man from the rural area of Eldorado.

On Thursday night [3 Nov 2002] he went to the emergency room for bleeding in the stool and a nosebleed, in addition to the fact that this man explained that 6 months ago he had a fever and weight loss.

When parasitic forms compatible with leishmaniasis, both intracytoplasmic and free, were detected in their analysis, the doctors launched the protocol for cases of visceral leishmaniasis, with hospitalization and specific treatment with liposomal amphotericin and transfusion support.

Despite the fact that the case was treated as positive due to the symptoms and the presence of the parasite, they still sent samples to LACMI [ Laboratorio de Alta Complejidad de Misiones, High Complexity Laboratory of Misiones province] to confirm visceral leishmaniasis by PCR.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED Rapporteur Mahmoud Orabi

---
[B]
Date: Tue 8 Nov 2022
Source: Misiones Online [in Spanish, machine trans., abridged, edited]
https://misionesonline.net/2022/11/08/leishmaniasis-enfermedad/


After having discovered the case of visceral leishmaniasis in a man from Eldorado, the director of Environmental Sanitation provided details about the disease and the procedures for possible cases.

The 1st thing that is done after medical diagnosis is the placement of traps in areas inhabited by the sandfly. These traps contain a light to attract sandflies. The traps are left at the optimal time, which is overnight and then the next day they are removed. The next procedure carried out by the Zoonosis Center is to study the sandfly and determine if it has consumed blood. Subsequently, chemical spraying is carried out in the vector's habitat.

Regarding the current case, on Thursday [10 Nov 2022], the municipality of Eldorado will conduct a survey of dogs in the area through serological testing. The procedure will continue on Friday [11 Nov 2022] with the placement of the sandfly traps and by the next day they will have figures on whether or not there is presence of leishmaniasis.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED Rapporteur Mahmoud Orabi

[Human visceral leishmaniasis is an emerging disease in Argentina that has been found in Misiones, Santiago del Estero, and Salta provinces (Ref. 1). Misiones province is in the extreme northeast of the country, straddling both Brazil and Paraguay. Argentina's 1st autochthonous case of HVL occurred there in Posadas in 2006, and was subsequently reported in 2014 in Puerto Iguazú, the Argentine gateway to the world-famous Iguazú Falls (Iguaçu Falls in Brazil). The case reported above is from El Dorado, which is located between Posada and Puerto Iguazú along Highway 12, which roughly follows the course of the Paraná River between Brazil and Argentina. The immediate testing of local dogs and captured phlebotomine sandflies to ascertain the presence of _L. infantum_ in the area is an excellent complement to parasitological and PCR testing of the human case.

A recent seroprevalence study of dogs in Puerto Iguazú found a rapid increase in canine infection with _L. infantum_, which is concerning because canine visceral leishmaniasis has been shown to precede outbreaks of HVL in Argentina (Ref. 2).

References:
1. Germano MJ, Salomón MC, Neira G, Lozano E, Mackern-Oberti JP, Cargnelutti DE. Leishmaniasis in the Argentine Republic: Temporal and geographical distribution from 2013 to 2017. Asian Pac J Trop Med 2019;12:300-5. https://www.apjtm.org/article.asp?issn=1995-7645;year=2019;volume=12;issue=7;spage=300;epage=305;aulast=Germano;type=0
2. Fujisawa K, Silcott-Niles C, Simonson P, Lamattina D, Humeres CA, Bhattacharyya T, Mertens P, Thunissen C, O'Rourke V, Pańczuk M, Whitworth JA, Salomón OD, Miles MA. Emergent canine visceral leishmaniasis in Argentina: Comparative diagnostics and relevance to proliferation of human disease. PLoS Negl Trop Dis. 19 Jul 2021;15(7):e0009552. doi: 10.1371/journal.pntd.0009552. PMID: 34280201; PMCID: PMC8289008. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC8289008/
- Mod.LXL

